"{\"uid\": \"nytimes.com-athletic-5297283-2024-02-26-nbc-olympics-ratings-paris-tv\", \"text\": \"Olympics    Follow our Olympics coverageto get all our stories on the road to Paris 2024 delivered to your feed.  Five months from now, on July 26, there will be an extraordinary scene on the River Seine in Paris. TheOlympicparade of athletes, normally held inside a massive stadium,will travel down the Seine featuring boatsfor each national delegation, equipped with cameras capturing the 10,500 athletes. The parade will cross through the center of Paris and conclude its 3.7-mile route in front of the Trocad\\u00e9ro, which offers a spectacular view of the Eiffel Tower. All of this will air live onNBC, Peacock and Telemundo.  The big question is: Will you be watching?  Advertisement  Olympic viewership has tumbled mightily in the United States since Rio de Janeiro in 2016. Those Brazil-based Games averaged a massive 27 million viewers in prime time, but since then, the key viewership arrow has been heading south. The Pyeongchang Winter Games in 2018 averaged 19.8 million viewers - a new low at the time that was later shattered by the Summer Olympics in Tokyo, which averaged 15.6 million viewers in prime time across NBC's various television and digital platforms in August 2021.Per Sports Media Watch,the Tokyo Games were the first Summer Olympics to average fewer American viewers than the preceding Winter Games since Athens in 2004, which followed Salt Lake City in 2002.  Then, the Beijing Winter Olympics in February 2022 were the least-watched Games in prime time on NBC ever,averaging 10.7 million viewers per night on television, with that number rising slightly to 11.4 million including all other viewing platforms.  Much of this, of course, was out of NBCUniversal's control. The Tokyo Games were delayed a year because of the coronavirus pandemic and the run-up to those Games was joyless given the state of the world. Complicating matters was the time zone - Tokyo is 13 hours ahead of the East Coast of the United States. The Beijing Games headwinds included a focus on the politics and human rights abuses in China, a global pandemic continuing to rage, a lack of household names compared to otherOlympics, and Olympic fatigue given the Tokyo Games wrapped up just six months earlier, among other reasons.  \\\"I see Paris as a chance for the Olympics to get its mojo back,\\\" said Bob Costas, who hosted NBC's prime-time Olympics coverage 11 times, a broadcasting standard that is unlikely to be topped. (Jim McKay hosted eight times for ABC.) \\\"The real problem \\u2026 came with the two COVID Olympics, one of which was postponed. With the absence of crowds and family and friends on hand, a lot of things that make the Olympics a great television show were missing. The absence of crowds for any sports event diminishes it greatly.  Advertisement  \\\"I think NBC coped with it as best they possibly could. They had cameras in a family's living room, but it's just not the same. So there is that. Plus, with the China Olympics, I think by then there was a broad understanding of something that I tried to make clear in 2008 (the Summer Olympics, which Beijing also hosted) and then again in 2014 (the Winter Games in Sochi, Russia), which is that the IOC has a troubling affinity for authoritarian regimes with horrible human rights records. I think by 2022 there was a broad public understanding of that, and with the other factors in it, it created a bad taste for a lot of people in the United States watching this.\\\"  But NBCU officials and Costas are rightly optimistic because Paris represents the beginning of a potentially terrific cycle for the Games. Paris, Milano-Cortina (2026) and Los Angeles (2028) are fantastic locations for an American broadcaster, especially home-based L.A. The advertising run-up seems to reflect the optimism. NBCUniversal president of Olympic and Paralympic partnerships Dan Lovinger told reporters last October that NBCUniversal ad sales for the 2024 Paris Olympics were outpacing any previous Games. The company confirmed this week the outlook remains the same. The time zone is not perfect - Paris is six hours ahead of Eastern Time - but it's much more viewer-friendly than Beijing.  Speaking of Paris, it's hard to think of a city with a better aesthetic for a television show. The host city and country has long been a central character for Olympic coverage, and NBC could not explore that in Tokyo and Beijing due to COVID restrictions. So expect NBC to highlight Paris with the same fervor ESPN once highlighted Tim Tebow. The Paris Games also have some ready-made stars scheduled to compete, including Simone Biles, LeBron James and Katie Ledecky. Women's sports is soaring at the moment, and transcendent athletes such as Sydney McLaughlin-Levrone are going to explode onto the public landscape.  Sports Media Watch editor Jon Lewis, who has chronicled Olympic viewership as tightly as anyone over the past 15 years, thinks viewership will be up but expressed some caution.  \\\"I think you will see Paris improve over Tokyo because of the COVID factor, as all of the COVID-era sporting events of 2020-21 had much smaller audiences, even the Super Bowl,\\\" Lewis said. \\\"Paris is one of the world's iconic cities, and that should help. Assuming Simone Biles is able to compete to the extent that she was in 2016, that should also help.  Advertisement  \\\"I would still expect viewership to be far closer to Tokyo 2021 than to London 2012. As to NBC airing marquee events outside of prime time, we are at a point in the history of television when trying to embargo live sporting events is pointless. NBC has in the past aired live coverage on platforms with limited distribution as a way to maintain said embargo while satisfying those who want to watch live. Might as well make sure the live coverage is available far and wide.\\\"  One media-centric question is whether these Olympics portend a shift in consumer habitswith Peacock streaming every event liveand on-demand, including all 329 medal events. (NBC will have at least nine hours of weekday daytime coverage, expanding to at least 11 hours on weekends. NBC said Paris 2024 will have more programming hours on the NBC broadcast network than any previous Olympics.)  The awareness of Peacock, which now has 30 million subscribers, is significantly higher than it was for the Tokyo Olympics, and no matter how you feel about theNFL's brazen money grab of putting a postseason game behind a paywall, Peacock proved it can aggregate a significant audience for sports. The Kansas City Chiefs-Miami Dolphins exclusive Peacock gamedrew 23 million viewers(including a substantial home-market turnout).  But Peacock being one of the hubs of the Games (along with NBC) is a shift, and we will see how many consumers get added. While everything will stream live from Paris in 2024, there is an argument to be made (and NBCU has made it) that viewers still want to sit down in prime time and watch a story told in front of them, even if they know the ending.  The ace in the hole for NBCU, at least from this corner, is the city of Paris. What made so many fall in love with the Olympics in years past was not just the incredible achievements of the athletes but being transported into a foreign wonderland.  \\\"I am fascinated by how the organizers plan to pull off the idea of the Opening ceremony going down the River Seine,\\\" said Costas, who left NBC in 2019. \\\"It has the potential to be unique and terrific. Then you have a Winter Olympics in Italy. Assuming that momentum has been established and is sustaining, now you come back to Los Angeles in 2028. I think this is the period of time where the Olympics itself, and the Olympics as a television entity, gets back on its feet despite all the changes in viewing habits and the media landscape.\\\"  Very cool in-boothNASCARfootage from Fox onthe incredible Cup Series finish in Atlantaon Sunday.  A behind-the-scenes view from the booth of that incredible Atlanta finish.#NASCAR@mikejoy500|@kevinharvick|@clintbowyerpic.twitter.com/yIfo2moKVy  - FOX: NASCAR (@NASCARONFOX)February 26, 2024    Episode 374 of the Sports Media Podcast  features Sue Bird, the five-time Olympic gold medalist, four-timeWNBAchampion, and the host of \\\"Sue's Places,\\\" an ESPN+ original series that features Bird exploring the history and traditions of college basketball.\\u00a0 In this podcast, Bird discusses athlete-owned media and the production company she and her fianc\\u00e9e, the soccer great Megan Rapinoe, recently formed; the influence of LeBron James on athlete-owned media production companies; how she views the traditional sports press; the Steph Curry versus Sabrina Ionescu 3-point shooting contest andKenny Smith's comments; and more.  Advertisement  Episode 375 of the Sports Media Podcastfeatures Sports Business Journal managing editor/digital Austin Karp. In this podcast, we discuss Daytona 500 viewership; how theNCAAbasketball tournaments should do viewership-wise; CNBC reporting that Amazon will pay $150 million to televise a wild-card playoff game to cap the 2024 season; EA Sports' new college football game, and more.  You can subscribe to this podcast on Apple Podcasts, Google Play, Spotify, and more.  -Jac Collinsworth is out as NBC's Notre Dame play-by-play voice,per Andrew Marchand, who reports Dan Hicks will replace Collinsworth and team up with analyst Jason Garrett.  - One thing I hope happens with NBCU's Paris Olympics coverage (and this is me saying it and not something Costas suggested): That NBC finds a role for Costas to narrate some historical-based pieces for the coverage. Like Jim McKay did with NBC after his hosting career ended, it just seems like a natural fit.  One of the best things you can say about someone in sports media - or any human, really - is that they pay it forward. If you are reading this column, there is a significant likelihood that you have heard of Peter King, the iconic NFL writer who covered the league for 40 years and announced on Monday thathe was stepping away from his job. What some of you do not know is how impactful King has been on the professional lives of many of the people you read today.  When King was at the height of his popularity at Sports Illustrated, where I was fortunate to work alongside him,he used his fame in 2013to launch a standalone football website, The MMQB. There were more talented writers at SI at the time, but no other staffer had his popularity (or web traffic), and by understanding the leverage he had, he became a sports digital trailblazer.  The MMQB legacy can be felt everywhere today, including alums such as Jenny Vrentas, Kalyn Kahler, Emily Kaplan, Robert Klemko, Greg Bedard, Jim Trotter and plenty of others. King asked me to write a weekly football-centric media column for his new site, and it was one of the coolest experiences I have had professionally, to be a tiny part of something with maniacal creative energy. It also helped keep me employed. The reality was that if Peter King was asking you to work on his site, SI management was not going to mess with you.  Advertisement  It was an honor to have a byline alongside those far more talented people and a lesson for me about how someone with media fame can create jobs for others. Thank you, Peter King.  Some things I have read recently that were interesting to me. (Note: There are many paywalls here.)  \\u2022 An old-school Las Vegas bookie takes on a new era of sports betting.By Danny Funt of The Washington Post.  \\u2022 A Family Ranch, Swallowed Up in the Madness of the Border.By Eli Saslow of The New York Times.  \\u2022 New Netflix Expos documentary bound to make us feel sad.By Brendan Kelly of the Montreal Gazette.  \\u2022 Hometown Hero JuJu Watkins Is Restoring Glory to USC Women's Basketball.By Emma Baccellieri of Sports Illustrated.  \\u2022 Inside North Korea's forced labor program.By Ian Urbina of The New Yorker.  \\u2022 Winnipeg Jets ownership sounds the alarm on attendance: 'Not going to work over the long haul.'By Chris Johnston ofThe Athletic.  \\u2022 Recovering the Lost Aviators of World War II.By\\u00a0Stephen Mihm of Smithsonian Magazine.  \\u2022 EA Sports College Football 25 offering players $600, copy of game as opt-in process opens.By Chris Vannini ofThe Athletic.  \\u2022 Why the Pirates keep losing.By Stephen J. Nesbitt\\u00a0and\\u00a0Ken Rosenthal ofThe Athletic.  \\u2022 Can Europe defend itself without America?By The Economist.  \\u2022 The issues with court storming.By William Weinbaum and Sara Coello of ESPN.  \\u2022 The $100 Bill Is America's Most Common Currency, and Its Most Annoying.By Oyin Adedoyin of The Wall Street Journal.  \\u2022 Want to Lose a Lot of Money, Fast? Buy a Small Soccer Team in England.By Rory Smith of The New York Times.  \\u2022 It's Been 30 Years Since the NBA's Last Quadruple-Double. Will We See Another Soon?By\\u00a0Zach Kram of The Ringer.  \\u2022 My NFL career ended with a needle and a scam.By Nate Jackson for Defector.  \\u2022 What AI Will Do to Elections.By Rishi Iyengar of Foreign Policy.  Advertisement  \\u2022 Who will draft Trevor Connelly? Inside theNHL's evolving scrutiny of top prospects.By Katie Strang\\u00a0and\\u00a0Corey Pronman ofThe Athletic.  \\u2022 An incredible piece. How Nikola Joki\\u0107 Became the World's Best Basketball Player.By\\u00a0Louisa Thomas of The New Yorker.  (Top photo of a boat passing by the Eiffel Tower during a 2023 test of the opening ceremony plan on the River Seine: Catherine Steenkeste / Getty Images)  Spot the pattern. Connect the terms  Find the hidden link between sports terms  Play today's puzzle\"}"